#3

plot(1:4, c(28.3, 26.9, 27.1, 28.7), type = "b", 
     xaxt = "n", xlab = "Year", 
     ylim = c(22, 30), ylab = "% of Adults", 
     main = "Cigarette Use in the U.S.")
lines(1:4, c(23.4, 23.1, 23, 23.4), type = "b", col = "red")
axis(1, at = 1:4, labels = 1999:2002)
legend("topleft", 
       legend = c("Male", "Female"), 
       lty = c(1, 1), 
       col = c("black", "red"))

Explanations:

  • plot function plots the data for the male group.
    • The first argument is the x-coordinates. 1:4 means 1, 2, 3, 4.
    • The second argument is the y-coordinates.
    • type = "b" means plot both data points and lines.
    • xaxt = "n" hides the x-axis ticks.
    • xlab is the x label.
    • ylim are the y value limits.
    • ylab is the y label.
    • main is the title of the graph.
  • line function adds the data for the female group.
    • col is the color of the line.
  • axis function writes the labels on the x axis. (Remember we hid the default ticks earlier?)
    • The first argument 1 means bottom axis. (FYI, 2 means left axis.)
    • at specifies the ticks at where we want to write the labels (i.e., 1, 2, 3 and 4).
    • labels adds the labels at the ticks we specified earlier. (i.e., put 1999 at x=1, 2000 at x=2, 2001 at x=3 and 2002 at x=4.)
  • legend function adds the legend to the graph.
    • The first argument is the location of the legend, e.g., topleft.
    • legend option specifies the words to be displayed as legend.
    • lty is the line type. 1 means solid line.

#11

12/2028 = 0.0059172

The event that two cards are of different suits has \(52\times 39 = 2028\) outcomes. (The first card can be any of the 52 cards. But once the first card is drawn, the second card is limited to one of the oher three suits, i.e., one of 39 cards.)

Of those 2028 outcomes, 12 are corresponding to both cards are aces. (The first card can be any of the four aces, then the second card can be any of the rest three aces.)

#41(a)

  • Let \(PHX\) be the event that it rains on the Phoenix trip.
  • Let \(LAX\) be the event that it rains on the Los Angeles trip.
  • Let \(MOB\) be the event that it rains on the Mobile trip. (\(MOB^c\) means no rain in the trip.)

The probability we are about to find out is

\[ P(PHX \cap LAX\cap MOB ) = P(PHX) \cdot P(LAX) \cdot P(MOB) = \frac{4}{31}\cdot\frac{3}{30}\cdot \frac{16}{31}=0.0066597,\\ \]

where \(P(MOB)=16/31\) because the trip is in July (which has 31 days) and the trip day could be any of the 16 rainy days of July.

Section 5.3

#29

Let \(X\) be the number of cakes sold. If the bakery bakes 2 cakes daily, then the probability distribution of \(X\) is

\(X\) \(P(X)\)
0 0.15
1 0.25
2 0.6
  • If no cake is sold, the profit is \(-4\times 2 = -8\) dollars. (Probability 0.15)
  • If one cake is sold, the profit is \(20 - 4\times 2 = 12\) dollars. (Probability 0.25)
  • If both cakes are sold, the profit is \(20\times 2 - 4 \times 2=32\) dollars. (Probability 0.6)

Therefore, if two cakes are baked daily, the expected profit is \[-8(0.15) + 12(0.25) + 32(0.6)=\$21.\]

Repeat the same process (reconstruct the probability distribution table) to find the expected profit for baking 3 and 4 cakes, separately. (Answer: $23 if 3 cakes are baked daily and $22 if 4 cakes are baked daily).

#3

\(E[\hat p]=p=0.1\), and \(SD(\hat p) = \sqrt{\dfrac{p(1-p)}{n}}=\sqrt{\dfrac{0.1(1-0.1)}{50}}\). By continuous correction,

  1. The approximate probability of getting no defective batteries is

    pnorm(0.5 / 50, 0.1, sqrt(0.1 * 0.9 / 50)) - pnorm(- 0.5 / 50, 0.1, sqrt(0.1 * 0.9 / 50))
    ## [1] 0.01218648

  2. The approximate probability of getting more than 15% defective batteries (i.e., 8 or more) in a sample of 50 is

    1 - pnorm(7.5 / 50, 0.1, sqrt(0.1 * 0.9 / 50))
    ## [1] 0.1192964

  3. The approximate probability of getting between 8% (i.e., 4) and 12% (i.e., 6) defective batteries in a sample of 50 is

    pnorm(6.5 / 50, 0.1, sqrt(0.1 * 0.9 / 50)) - pnorm(3.5 / 50, 0.1, sqrt(0.1 * 0.9 / 50))
    ## [1] 0.5204999

#5

\(E[\hat p]=p=0.092\), and \(SD(\hat p) = \sqrt{\dfrac{p(1-p)}{n}}=\sqrt{\dfrac{0.092(1-0.092)}{400}}\). By continuous correction,

  1. The approximate probability that 40 or fewer German workers were unemployed is

    pnorm(40.5 / 400, 0.092, sqrt(0.092 * (1 - 0.092) / 400))
    ## [1] 0.73894

  2. The approximate probability that more than 50 German workers were unemployed is

    1 - pnorm(50.5 / 400, 0.092, sqrt(0.092 * (1 - 0.092) / 400))
    ## [1] 0.008893335

## [1] 0.04160677

Conclusion: Based on a 0.05 significance level, the p-value is small. We reject the null hypothesis. There is sufficient evidence to show that the new drug is more effective than the old one.

#1

Let \(\mu\) be the actual distance from Earth to the asteroid Phyla.

  • \(H_0: \mu = 14.4\)
  • \(H_1: \mu \ne 14.4\)
  • The sample mean is \(\bar{x}=14.717\). Thus the test statistic is \(\dfrac{14.717 - 14.4}{0.5/\sqrt{6}}=1.55\).
  • P-value \(= 2\times P(\bar{x} > 14.717) = 0.12\)
2 * (1 - pnorm(1.55))
## [1] 0.1211415

Based on a 005 significance level, the p-value is not small. Therefore, we do not reject the null hypothesis, which means there is no sufficient evidence to show that the actual distance from Earth to the asteroid Phyla is different from 14.4 light years.

#1

  • Let \(\mu_1\) be the true systolic blood pressure for all smokers.
  • Let \(\mu_2\) be the true systolic blood pressure for all nonsmokers.
  • \(H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2\)
  • \(H_1: \mu_1 \ne \mu_2\)
s <- c(124, 134, 136, 125, 133, 127, 135, 131, 133, 125, 118)
ns <- c(130, 122, 128, 129, 118, 122, 116, 127, 135, 120, 122, 120, 115, 123)
t.test(s, ns, alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  s and ns
## t = 2.5239, df = 21.636, p-value = 0.01947
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   1.033961 10.615390
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  129.1818  123.3571
  • Based on a significance level of 0.01, the p-value is not small. We do not reject the null hypothesis. There is no sufficient evidence to show that the mean systolic blood pressure levels are different between smokers and nonsmokers.
  • Based on a significance level of 0.05, the p-value is small. We reject the null hypothesis. There is sufficient evidence to show that the mean systolic blood pressure levels are different between smokers and nonsmokers.

#3(c)

To find the line equation:

distance <- c(5.2, 4.4, 3, 1.2, 7.5, 9.4)
damage <- c(36.2, 28.8, 22.6, 8.8, 41.5, 25.4)
lm(damage ~ distance)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = damage ~ distance)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)     distance  
##      14.787        2.429

In case you would like to know how to add the line to the scatter plot, here it is. (Google pch in r to see the list of available markers.)

plot(damage ~ distance, pch = 15,
     xlab = 'Distance to the nearest fire station',
     ylab = "Damage ($1000)")
abline(lm(damage ~ distance), col = 'red', lwd = 2)
